94795,0.022355091700494795,0.04471018340098959,0,0.022355091700494795,0.04471018340098959,0.04471018340098959,0.022355091700494795,0.022355091700494795,0.04471018340098959,0.022355091700494795,0,0,0.022355091700494795,0,0,0.06706527510148438,0.08942036680197918,0.022355091700494795,0.022355091700494795,0.17884073360395836,0.022355091700494795,0,0.04471018340098959,0.04471018340098959]},{"id":"pcos_overview-1","text":"Managing PCOS\nHealthy lifestyle steps are usually the first-line help: a balanced diet, regular physical activity, and reaching or keeping a healthy weight can improve periods and symptoms. A doctor may also suggest specific treatments depending on whether a woman wants to manage symptoms or become pregnant. PCOS is also linked with a higher long-term risk of type 2 diabetes, so regular check-ups help.","title":"Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)","source":"WHO fact sheet (sample seed — replace with the licensed source text before submission)","url":"https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/polycystic-ovary-syndrome","embedding":[0.10724978403434372,0.13406223004292966,0,0,0,0.02681244600858593,0.02681244600858593,0,0.05362489201717186,0.02681244600858593,0,0.02681244600858593,0,0,0,0.02681244600858593,0.02681244600858593,0,0.13406223004292966,0,0,0.0804373380257578,0.02681244600858593,0.1608746760515156,0.02681244600858593,0,0,0.02681244600858593,0.1608746760515156,0.13406223004292966,0,0,0,0.02681244600858593,0.05362489201717186,0.05362489201717186,0.10724978403434372,0.02681244600858593,0.02681244600858593,0.0804373380257578,0,0.02681244600858593,0.05362489201717186,0,0.26812446008585933,0,0.05362489201717186,0,0,0.05362489201717186,0,0,0.05362489201717186,0,0.02681244600858593,0,0.0804373380257578,0.02681244600858593,0,0,0,0,0,0.02681244600858593,0.10724978403434372,0.0804373380257578,0.10724978403434372,0,0,0.0804373380257578,0,0.10724978403434372,0,0.02681244600858593,0,0.0804373380257578,0,0.1608746760515156,0.05362489201717186,0.053624892