.02681244600858593,0,0,0,0,0.05362489201717186,0,0.10724978403434372,0.02681244600858593,0.1608746760515156,0.13406223004292966,0.05362489201717186,0.05362489201717186,0,0.05362489201717186]},{"id":"who_iron_anaemia_pregnancy-0","text":"Why iron matters in pregnancy\nAnaemia (low blood / কম রক্ত) is common in pregnancy and can make a woman feel very tired, weak, or dizzy. Severe anaemia raises the risk of problems during delivery.\n\nRecommended supplementation\nWHO recommends daily oral iron and folic acid supplementation for pregnant women to prevent maternal anaemia. A commonly recommended dose is 30–60 mg of elemental iron together with 400 micrograms (0.4 mg) of folic acid daily, throughout pregnancy, starting as early as possible.\n\nFood and follow-up\nIron-rich foods (green leafy vegetables, liver, meat, beans, dates) help alongside the supplement. Vitamin C foods (lemon, guava) help the body absorb iron. A woman who feels very weak, breathless, or dizzy should see a doctor or health worker, who may check her blood (haemoglobin) level.","title":"Iron and anaemia in pregnancy","source":"WHO (sample seed — replace with the licensed source text before submission)","url":"https://www.who.int/tools/elena/interventions/daily-iron-pregnancy","embedding":[0.048143488852893324,0,0,0.03209565923526221,0.016047829617631106,0.09628697770578665,0.06419131847052442,0.08023914808815553,0.016047829617631106,0,0.016047829617631106,0,0,0.03209565923526221,0.03209565923526221,0,0,0.016047829617631106,0.048143488852893324,0,0,0.08023914808815553,0.03209565923526221,0.12838263694104884,0,0.016047829617631106,0,0.03209565923526221,0.16047829617631107,0,0.09628697770578665,0,0.1925739554115733,0.06419131847052442,0.06419131847052442,0.048143488852893324,0.03209565923526221,0.06419131847052442,0.03209565923526221,0.06419131847052442,0,0.016047829617631106,0.03209565923526221,0,0.12838263694104884,0.048143488852893324,0.11233480732341775,0.048143488852893324,0.016047829617631106,0,0